step.tex:
\begin{align}
\dfrac{\cos 2 x}{(\cos x+\sin  x)^2} 
&= \dfrac{\cos 2 x}{\cos^2 x+\sin^2  x + 2 \sin x \cos x} \\

&= \dfrac{\cos 2x}{1 + \sin 2x}
\end{align} \\

\therefore 
\int \dfrac{\cos 2 x}{(\cos x+\sin  x)^2} \, dx = \int \dfrac{\cos 2x}{1 + \sin 2x} \, dx\\

step.reason:
\text{Applied the trigonometric identity, }\\
\sin^2 x + \cos^2 x = 1 \text{ and }
\sin 2x = 2 \sin x \cos x \\
\text{Check your calculations, if you got something}\\
\text{else.}
